            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Meiko Wong\u2019s life is a story told in fabric and numbers. The only child of Hong Kong immigrants, she grew up amidst the steam and meticulous precision of her parents\u2019 dry-cleaning business in the Richmond District. While her parents preached pragmatism and security, Meiko was quietly captivated by the textures, colors, and silhouettes of the garments entrusted to their care. She learned the difference between silk and rayon not in a classroom, but by feel, developing an innate sense of quality and style.\n\nHer path seemed set when she pursued an Economics degree at UC Berkeley, a nod to her parents' values. However, her true passion simmered. The turning point was a post-graduation internship at a small San Francisco boutique. There, surrounded by emerging designers, she realized her love for fashion wasn't a hobby; it was a viable career. This was her quiet rebellion\u2014not against her family, but for herself. She took a calculated leap, enrolling in an MBA program with a focus on retail management to merge her creative eye with sharp business acumen.\n\nNow, at 30, Meiko is a Senior Apparel Buyer for a major national retailer. Her days are a high-stakes blend of analyzing sales data, negotiating with vendors, and forecasting trends months in advance. Her 3.8-mile Muni commute from her chic Hayes Valley apartment to her downtown office is a cherished ritual, a time to decompress with podcasts before the pressure begins.\n\nHer life is woven into the city's fabric. Weekends are for jogging through Golden Gate Park, discovering new restaurants with her long-term partner, Alex, a software engineer, and browsing the very boutiques that first inspired her. Though her $155,000 salary affords a comfortable lifestyle, she remains grounded by her upbringing. Meiko dreams of one day launching her own sustainable clothing line\u2014a brand that would honor the quality her parents taught her while fully embracing the innovative, forward-thinking spirit of San Francisco, the city she unequivocally calls home."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was eight, hiding behind the poly-wrapped racks as the press hissed steam. A customer had left a vibrant emerald silk blouse, and Meiko\u2019s small fingers reached out to trace the cool, smooth fabric. It felt like liquid light. In that secret touch, amidst the scent of cleaning chemicals, she understood that beauty wasn't just pragmatic; it was essential. That stolen moment, feeling the story in the threads, planted the seed of her true calling, a world away from the shop\u2019s daily ledger.\n\n***\n\n2.\nAt 21, during her post-grad boutique internship, she unpacked a box from a new Mission-based designer. Inside was a structured wool coat with an impossibly perfect asymmetrical collar. Holding it, she felt a certainty that eclipsed all her economic formulas. It wasn't just clothing; it was architecture and emotion. This was her language. The feeling wasn't rebellion against her parents' path, but a quiet, firm declaration for her own. She started her MBA application that night.\n\n***\n\n3.\nJogging with Alex in Golden Gate Park a few years ago, they stopped near the Conservatory of Flowers. Bathed in the late afternoon sun, the white structure looked like intricate lacework against the sky. Alex squeezed her hand, sensing her awe. In that shared, wordless moment, Meiko felt the city wasn't just a place she lived, but a partner in her life. The natural, elegant design reminded her of her own dream\u2014to create something beautiful and enduring right here.\n\n***\n\n4.\nLast Tuesday, the 21-Hayes bus crested the hill, revealing the downtown skyline against a pink-grey dawn. With a podcast on supply chains in her earbuds, she felt a surge of quiet gratitude. This commute\u2014the rumbling bus, the diverse faces, the city unfolding\u2014was her sacred space. It was the seam connecting her personal life to her professional ambition. This daily journey reminded her that she wasn't just working in the city; she was woven into its very rhythm.\n\n***\n\n5.\nLast year, she visited her parents at the shop. An old client brought in a vintage cashmere coat with a torn lining. Meiko took it, her fingers instinctively assessing the weave. She sat with her mother, making tiny, invisible stitches\u2014a skill learned through childhood observation. Her father nodded in quiet approval. In that simple act of repair, she felt the fusion of their world and hers: the pragmatism of a perfect stitch, preserving an object of beauty. It solidified her sustainable dream."
